text: ah hi everyone Anthony fartface here the
Internet's busiest music nerd and it is
time for a review of the new Oliver tree
album ugly is beautiful this is the
long-awaited pushed back and now
eventually released debut full-length
album of singer-songwriter
multi-instrumentalist producer director
meme master
Oliver tree been pretty excited for this
one to drop not only because my first
introduction to Oliver was a very fun
live show where he showcased his
exuberant songs that celebrated many
things from 90s music culture the rock
the pop the hip hop of that era but with
a modern punch but he also carries and
promotes himself much more creatively
and eccentrically than many artists out
there today his i grabbing fashion sense
his wild music video concepts his viral
memes and the sense that he's always in
character to some degree it's all
reflective of a level of showmanship
that I feel like many artists are just
not willing to commit to in the social
media age where nothing is really hidden
in the shadows anymore but despite this
societal paradigm shift Oliver has still
been able to deliver this seamless image
of a bulkheaded weirdo who's always
caught in these super exaggerated absurd
situations so while it is admirable what
Oliver has been able to pull off on the
lower end of things his new record still
didn't get the rollout the promotional
rollout it deserved with Oliver building
up anticipation with one EP and another
EP and then single after single after
single after single after single in tons
of music videos and it just got to the
point where much of the surprise of this
record was pretty much spoiled or just
stale at this point however I will say
there is something to be gained by
hearing all of these songs in the
greater context of an album because if
there is any branch of Oliver trees art
where he's kind of removing the jacket
the balke and the glasses it's his music
as in the lyrics of his songs there are
consistent themes of being discounted
written off
neglected forgotten
streeted feeling like an outcast feeling
like a joke [ __ ] up having insecurity
the track 1993 isn't just titled after
the year Oliver was born but it's also a
song where lyrically he goes on about
beginning to achieve his dreams saying
that there are no guarantees in his
unquenchable thirst for success while
also making a bit of meta commentary on
pretending to be someone else in the
second half so if you find that Oliver's
music seems to lack the surrealism that
nearly every other piece of art he makes
has it's because he's kind of just being
himself considering that there are some
moments on this LP like jerk which are
narrative ly tragic where Oliver finds
himself cutting things off entirely with
a person preferring isolation and
loneliness over the emotional trauma
this individual brings him or even the
track I'm gone which is a sad howling
fuzzy semi demented indie rock rager
where Oliver is singing about being gone
essentially where he's just paralyzed by
indecision it seems like a send-off
where he's bowing out of public life or
art or out of something else more
personal I'm not entirely sure but then
going on about how they will always find
you
I can't quite put it into words but it's
like there's a breadcrumb trail being
left for fans on this song who might
want to know he's doing after this
record in regards to the songwriting on
this LP every single track on this album
is very very tightly structured almost
to a fault sometimes because there are
points where Oliver I think could be
extending things a bit adding more
lyrics a different or a fresh verse but
there is no doubt about the fact that
Oliver knows his way around a hook even
on the weakest tracks of this LP the
choruses are popping and honestly as I
listen to the entire album even the
songs that I am the most familiar with
in the tracklist haven't really lost
their luster they're still very fun to
listen to the song alien boy which is
still a very groovy and stark piece of
pop music with nasally lead vocals that
cut like a knife and super bubbly synth
leads there is the song hurt which is a
punchy and moody combination of rock and
hip-hop that features a super shouty
refrain that grabbed my ears right away
seems like it never really was enough
then the song introspective is a sad
piece of slacker rock with somewhat
distorted in twangy rhythm guitars
bittersweet lead vocals as well that
feel genuinely pained and Oliver's
really pushing the odd timbre of his
voice on this track to the point where
he sounds like he's a bleeding sheep and
I mean that in the best way possible it
does stand out and it's not grating
stylistically and emotionally I get a
similar quality off of the song miracle
man too but this one by contrast is
backed by these peppy driving sequenced
beats and a very solid set of acoustic
guitar chords yeah there are also some
deeper highlights on this LP that I love
too namely the tracks joke's on you as
well as bury me alive where Oliver
really shows off his rap skills his
delivery makes him sound like a Beastie
Boys member in his prime going solo
flowing like a river and not that it's a
bad thing but when Oliver wraps on this
LP I feel like that's the closest he
comes to sounding like he's in character
when he's making his music while I'm
mentioning highlights let me dial it
back one more time to the song 1993
which might just have the sickest groove
on the entire record that bass line the
growling thumping gritty house beat on
this track is stellar then there's also
the traps which up toward the end which
I believe features some vocals from
little Ricky's er three on it seemed
like it made for a very murky and deep
and dark section of the track that was
kind of cool for the ending so again
those are the highlights for me but
where this record falters the most is on
the compositional end or the
instrumental and where the ideas
presented are so stale and done to death
they feel derivative of a handful of
other things the kind of stuff that I
used to hear played on the radio to
death during the 90s when I was a kid
believe it or not there are even spots
of this LP where the combination of rap
and rock and pop seems kind of
reminiscent of twenty one pilots there's
the opening track which sounds like a
ripoff of a stroke song then the song
again and again feels like a kind of
mediocre take on Cage the Elephant ever
thing from the guitars to the drums to
the breakdown on the pre-chorus and the
riff that pops in and the super like
high-pitched yeah vocal delivery that
Oliver busts out during that moment just
seems like the exact kind of fuzzy
garage rock revivalism that caged the
elephant has kind of already nailed then
there's the track waste my time which i
think is my least favorite here not
because it sounds like anything else but
because Oliver is really leaning into
the most unlikable qualities of his
voice on this song to the point where it
just gets annoying if this song is
trying to rub me the wrong way it's
working
overall though I did like this album I
think it's a pretty solid debut despite
it not being rolled out in the most
perfect way but I still wonder where is
Oliver going to go from here what is he
going to do if you call back to my
recent interview with him he said this
is going to be his last record that's
kind of disheartening because I do hear
a ton of potential in the future of
Oliver tree after having heard this it
kind of feels like the sky could be the
limit past this point but now I guess
the ride is over
feeling a decent too strong 7 on this
one transition have you given this album
